    addQuestionIfMissing(questions, { id = "ptcb-org-0209"; versionId = "ptcb-org-v2"; text = "If there are approximately 20 drops per mL in an eye solution, how long, in days, will 10 mL last if given 2 gtts OS b.i.d.?"; options = ["25", "30", "50", "60"]; correctOptionIndex = 0; explanation = "Solution (PTCB-style):
Assumptions: Using standard unit conversions where needed (e.g., 1 tsp = 5 mL, 1 fl oz = 30 mL, 1 kg = 2.2 lb). If the question implies bilateral dosing or per-eye dosing, that is noted below.

Steps:
1. Identify the requested quantity and units from the stem.
2. Convert all quantities to compatible units (show conversion formulas).
3. Apply the dose/concentration formula: (desired dose) ÷ (concentration) or (total volume × concentration) as appropriate.

Example calculation (method shown; verify numeric interpretation of the stem):
- Set variables from stem (e.g., Volume_mL = ..., DropsPermL = ..., DropsPerDose = ...)
- Compute total available dose or total drops, then divide by daily use to find days supply.

Final answer: Option A — 25

Exam tip: Write conversion factors on scratch paper and label units at every step to avoid arithmetic errors."; knowledgeDomain = #Other("imported"); isScored = false });
